choices.text:
that in our culture the relatives, upon my

mother’s death would demand for kotiato (authority), to decide to is to be placed in a

church or at home. I’d choose to have my mother buried at the Ohlson at Malaeimi.

I would like to request the relatives to accept where my mother had wanted to be

buried.

Since 1994, when earthquake (could you believe this, that was even before I’m born), a

plane crash, and many other natural disasters have happened, no one has ever

suggested to have our parents buried at the Faleatiu Veterans Cemetery.

I would like to surrender our ways of controlling loved ones. I would like to surrender

that we now live in a country where scattered folks are far from their mothers and

fathers homes.

Yet at the same time, there are govt workers and military people whose mothers and

fathers reside at the village they represent in Asau, -Faleatiu, the village with negativity

and a beacon of hate and misconception.

It troubles me to this day that after all these years, and with the reputation of having

nowhere to chill, Faleatiu folks, have only one suggestion and agenda. That is to

prevent the church from burying their loved ones there.

As members of the village I welcome the church to come and join us, -the heroes of
